                <h2 class=3D"text question" style=3D"font-size:medium; font=
-style:italic;">Is linear programming useful in real life?</h2>
                <div class=3D"alignright display-mobile nomargin hide-print=
" style=3D"width:180px; min-height:215px;"><!-- contracted ad for mobile --=
>
                  <p class=3D"in-lesson-resp-ad-header nomargin" align=3D"c=
enter">Affiliate</p>
                  <div id=3D"contract_ad" class=3D"cookieconsent-optin-mark=
eting" style=3D"text-align:center; margin:10px 0px 10px 15px;">
                    <ins data-revive-zoneid=3D"2" data-revive-id=3D"22fb12d=
5af67c91fb385a68f631b6803"></ins>
                   =20
                  </div>
                </div><!-- /contracted ad for mobile -->
                <div class=3D"hide-mobile hide-print" style=3D"width:300px;=
 min-height:270px; float:right; margin-left:10px;">
                <!-- non-mobile box -->
                <p class=3D"in-lesson-resp-ad-header">Advertisement</p>
                  <ins data-revive-zoneid=3D"9" data-revive-id=3D"22fb12d5a=
f67c91fb385a68f631b6803"></ins>
                 =20
                </div><!-- /non-mobile box ad -->
                <p class=3D"text">In real life, linear programming is part =
of a very important area of mathematics called "optimization techniques".</=
p>
                <p class=3D"text">This field of study (or at least the appl=
ied results of it) are used every day in the organization and allocation of=
 resources. These real life systems can have dozens of variables, or hundre=
ds, or more. (For the curious, a history of linear programming: <a href=3D"=
https://www.math.uni-bielefeld.de/documenta/vol-ismp/25_bixby-robert.pdf">P=
DF</a>)</p>
                <p class=3D"text">In algebra, though, you'll only work with=
 the simple (and graphable) two-variable linear case.</p>
                <h2 class=3D"text question" style=3D"font-size:medium; font=
-style:italic;">How do you solve a linear programming problem?</h2>
                <div class=3D"alignright display-mobile hide-print" style=
=3D"width:180px; float:right; margin-left:10px; margin-top:20px;">
                <!-- WyzAnt mobile-only ad -->
                  <p class=3D"in-lesson-resp-ad-header nomargin" align=3D"c=
enter">Affiliate</p>
                  <div id=3D"WyzAnt_Widget" class=3D"alignright" style=3D"m=
ax-width:160px;">
                    <div class=3D"wyzant wyzant-widget" data-widget-type=3D=
"side-search" data-api-key=3D"db8aced3-1979-4f99-bec1-650e0dfcb678" data-su=
bject=3D"algebra" data-size=3D"5" data-channel-id=3D"17"><div class=3D"side=
-widget side-widget-search"><div class=3D"logo"><img src=3D"https://partner=
-tools.wyzantcdn.com/sprocket/src/images/wyzant-logo.png"></div><p>Affordab=
le tutors for hire</p><form class=3D"form"><input type=3D"text" name=3D"sub=
ject" class=3D"form-control" placeholder=3D"Enter Subject" value=3D"algebra=
"><button type=3D"submit" class=3D"btn btn-block btn-primary"><i class=3D"w=
yzant-icon wyzant-icon-search"></i>Find tutors</button></form></div></div>
                  </div>
                </div><!-- /WyzAnt mobile-only ad -->
                <p class=3D"text">The general process for solving linear-pr=
ogramming exercises is as follows:</p>
                <ol>
                  <li class=3D"text"><a href=3D"https://www.purplemath.com/=
modules/syslneq.htm">Graph</a> the system of linear inequalities. The area =
walled off by the various inequalities is called the "feasibility region".<=
/li>
                  <li class=3D"text">Taking the "equals" versions of the in=
equalities, solve pairs of lines to find the corner points (or "vertices") =
of the feasibility region.</li>
                  <li class=3D"text">Plug the coordinates of each of the ve=
rtices into the model for the situation at hand (that is, into the optimiza=
tion equation).</li>
                  <li class=3D"text">If you're maximizing, take the corner =
that gives you the highest value; otherwise, take the one with the lowest v=
alue.</li>
                  <li class=3D"text">For word problems, interpret the resul=
t within the context given (for example, say "eight meters wide and three m=
eters tall" rather than just "<span class=3D"math">(8,&nbsp;3)</span>").
                </li></ol>
                <h2 class=3D"text question" style=3D"font-size:medium; font=
-style:italic;">Why do you test only the corners?</h2>
                <p class=3D"text">Somebody figured out that, given a system=
 of linear inequalities and an equation to be optimized (that is, to be max=
imized or minimized), the system's optimal solution will always be on a cor=
ner.</p>
                <p class=3D"text">There are <a href=3D"https://faculty.math=
.illinois.edu/~mlavrov/docs/482-fall-2019/lecture8.pdf">complicated</a> exp=
lanations for this, but also <a href=3D"https://math.stackexchange.com/ques=
tions/2502781/why-are-corner-points-of-feasible-region-candidates-in-solvin=
g-linear-programmin#answer-2502823">intuitive</a> ones (for the simple two-=
variable case that we'll be working with). Either way, the corners are wher=
e it's at.</p>
